{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522284"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13817"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13817"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.09,0.17,0.14,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6434"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103917"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6434"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13817"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86323"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"1470"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37074"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103917"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of severe eye pain, this being worse in her right eye, associated with redness and photophobia. She reports that the pain worsens with eye movement. She has a medical history of rheumatoid arthritis, diagnosed 10 years ago and is currently taking methotrexate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Ocular examination reveals diffuse redness of the sclera in her right eye (Image), with tenderness on palpation. Visual acuity is 6/9 in the right eye and 6/6 in the left eye. Slit lamp examination shows no corneal involvement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravitreal triamcinolone injection","Topical antibiotics","Lubricating eye drops","Oral non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs","Oral prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features consistent with scleritis in the context of rheumatoid arthritis. Scleritis is a serious, potentially sight-threatening condition that requires prompt and aggressive treatment, especially in patients with underlying autoimmune diseases. Patients typically present with a history of severe piercing eye pain over days and worse with movement, and have a violet-bluish hue with scleral oedema and dilatation on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial management in this case would be to start \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E with rheumatology referral. Oral prednisolone provides systemic immunosuppression, which is crucial for managing scleritis in the context of rheumatoid arthritis. The rheumatology referral is important for optimising the patient\u0027s overall immunosuppressive regimen and potentially adjusting her current rheumatoid arthritis medications. This approach addresses both the acute ocular inflammation and the underlying systemic disease, reducing the risk of recurrence and complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELubricating eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E alone are usually insufficient for treating scleritis, particularly in patients with rheumatoid arthritis. Lubricating drops do not address the underlying inflammatory process and are generally used for symptomatic relief in conditions like dry eye alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful for mild to moderate cases of scleritis, they are unlikely to be sufficient in this patient with severe symptoms and underlying rheumatoid arthritis. More potent immunosuppression is typically required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in this case as there is no evidence of an infectious process such as conjunctivitis. Scleritis in the context of rheumatoid arthritis is an inflammatory condition, not an infectious one.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravitreal triamcinolone injection\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard treatment for scleritis. This approach is more commonly used for certain retinal conditions and would not address the underlying systemic inflammatory process in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Scleritis associated with rheumatoid arthritis often requires systemic immunosuppression for effective management.","Prompt recognition and treatment of scleritis is crucial to prevent vision-threatening complications."],"references":["Bunya V. Scleritis. In: EyeWiki American Academy of Opthalmology [online]. 2024. Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Scleritis","Khan J, Mack H. Management of conjunctivitis and other causes of red eye during the COVID-19 pandemic. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020: 49 (10). Available in: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/october/management-of-conjunctivitis-and-other-causes-of-r","Promelle V, Goeb V, Gueudry J. Rheumatoid Arthritis Associated Episcleritis and Scleritis: An Update on Treatment Perspectives. J Clin Med. 2021 May 14;10(10):2118. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8156434/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86323"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13817"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20764"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20764"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/FwODdiFWlY4E1kaI2xqWdijsMIpUGM.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/FwODdiFWlY4E1kaI2xqWdijsMIpUGM.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86323"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-28T09:17:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-28T09:17:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6434"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103917"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rela